  "prompt": "How should you treat a bump on your eyeball?",
  "response": "If you notice a bump on your eyeball or the surrounding area, it's essential to approach the situation carefully. Here are steps you should take:\n\n1. **Do Not Touch or Rub Your Eye**: Avoid touching or rubbing the area, as this can exacerbate irritation or cause injury.\n\n2. **Assess the Symptoms**: Take note of any accompanying symptoms, such as redness, pain, swelling, changes in vision, or discharge. This information can be helpful for a healthcare professional.\n\n3. **Avoid Self-Medication**: Do not attempt to treat the bump with over-the-counter medications or home remedies without consulting a professional first.\n\n4. **Seek Medical Attention**: It's crucial to see an eye doctor (ophthalmologist) or a healthcare professional as soon as possible. They can provide a proper diagnosis and treatment plan. \n\n5. **Provide Information**: When you visit the doctor, be prepared to provide details about how long the bump has been there, any changes in your vision, and any other symptoms you may be experiencing.\n\nCommon causes of bumps on the eyeball can include:\n\n- **Pinguecula**: A yellowish, benign growth on the eye's surface.\n- **Pterygium**: A growth of fleshy tissue on the conjunctiva that can extend onto the cornea.\n- **Cysts**: Fluid-filled sacs that can develop on the conjunctiva.\n- **Eyelid conditions**: Such as styes (infections of oil glands at the eyelid margin) or chalazia.\n\nRemember, only a medical professional can accurately diagnose and appropriately treat any eye condition.",
